 From Ratings to Returns:
 Peer Information,
 Farmer Beliefs,
 and Technology Adoption under Performance Uncertainty
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Peer Information,
 Farmer Beliefs,
 and Technology Adoption under Performance Uncertainty:
 Experimental Evidence from Uganda
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Many smallholder farmers in low- and middle-income countries do not adopt modern agricultural inputs sold by agro-dealers due to uncertainty about their performance.
 We introduce a system that aggregates farmers’ evaluations of seed into ratings and disseminates them to farmers and agro-dealers,
 providing a summary signal of seed performance based on peers’ experiences.
 We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial involving 3,500 farmers and 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize seed in Uganda.
 We hypothesize that the intervention operates through two complementary channels.
 On the demand side,
 exposure to peer ratings increases farmers’ perceptions of seed performance,
 with effects concentrated among farmers without prior purchasing experience —
 those whose beliefs are most likely to diverge from the experiences of actual purchasers.
 This leads to higher adoption of high-yielding maize seed and 13% higher yields,
 reflecting both a shift toward improved varieties and increased investment in complementary inputs.
 On the supply side,
 agro-dealers report improving service provision and signaling professionalism,
 though not seed handling or storage practices.
 The demand-side evidence is stronger and more consistent:
 the concentration of effects among non-purchasers suggests that the gap between these farmers’ beliefs and purchasers’ reported experiences is a binding constraint on adoption.
 We find no evidence that the intervention operates through changes in underlying seed performance or farmers’ choice of agro-dealers.
\end_layout

