\begin_layout Standard
Smallholder farmers in low- and middle-income countries adopt productivity-enhancing agricultural inputs,
 such as improved seeds and inorganic fertilizers,
 at persistently low rates despite their potential to increase agricultural productivity,
 improve food security,
 and reduce poverty.
 A large literature examines the reasons for this limited adoption.
 As reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/jep.36.1.33"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 proposed explanations include credit,
 liquidity,
 and savings constraints;
 limited access to insurance;
 information frictions;
 high transaction costs and poor infrastructure;
 and imperfections in labor and land markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important additional explanation is that farmers hold uncertain beliefs about the performance of agricultural inputs supplied by agro-dealers,
 the primary distribution channel for improved seed varieties 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,MICHELSON2023102424,dar2020private"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the market for high-yielding maize seed in Uganda,
 several studies document substantial performance uncertainty:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this study,
 the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-yielding maize varieties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to both open-pollinated varieties (OPVs) and hybrids that have been genetically improved through breeding programs.
 We explain the terminology and our rationale for using this terminology in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.1 Context on seeds and their quality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bold2017lemon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that locally sold hybrid seed contains less than 50% authentic seed.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 document improper handling and storage of maize seed purchased from retailers,
 while 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ilukor2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that seed quality declines along the supply chain relative to samples obtained directly from seed companies.
 These studies document that seed quality varies substantially across sellers and over time,
 but this variation is largely invisible to farmers at the point of purchase.
 The resulting belief uncertainty directly discourages adoption by increasing the perceived riskiness of purchasing from agro-dealers.
 Moreover,
 negative information about seed quality tends to be more salient and spreads faster than positive experiences 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "neg_bias,vaish2008not,hornik2015information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which can push uncertain beliefs toward pessimism.
 Adoption decisions therefore depend crucially on farmers’ beliefs about the performance of seed purchased from agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performance uncertainty also distorts the use of complementary inputs:
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bulte2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that uncertain farmers allocate less labor,
 reducing yields and making it harder to learn about the true profitability of improved varieties.
 More broadly,
 learning from own experience is difficult because agricultural outcomes depend on many factors beyond seed performance,
 and information from social networks is limited to a small number of peers whose experiences may not generalize.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "laajaj_macours_forthcoming"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show more broadly that agricultural learning is inherently multidimensional and that even with intensive exposure,
 peer-to-peer transfer of knowledge about input performance faces severe frictions.
 These learning constraints allow imprecise or biased beliefs to persist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existing mechanisms that aim to provide credible signals about seed performance have important limitations.
 Seed companies signal quality through labeling and packaging,
 but farmers struggle to identify low-quality seed without specific training 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gharib2021fear"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Regulatory certification systems are costly and,
 in Uganda,
 do not provide a reliable signal of performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/1477-9552.70002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 these signals only reach farmers who already engage with agro-dealers,
 and even certified seed may perform poorly where handling and storage are inadequate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper,
 we test a decentralized alternative:
 rather than relying on top-down certification,
 we aggregate the experiences of farmers themselves into a signal of seed performance.
 Building on a well-established literature documenting the importance of peers in agricultural technology adoption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foster1995learning,https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0297.2006.01115.x,10.1257/aer.100.1.35"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we test whether aggregating peers’ experiences can reduce the uncertainty and pessimism that characterize farmers’ beliefs about seed performance.
 We introduce a system that collects farmers’ evaluations of maize seed purchased from agro-dealers and aggregates them into ratings that summarize the experiences of multiple farmers facing similar conditions.
 These ratings are disseminated to both farmers and agro-dealers,
 providing a summary signal about seed performance at agro-dealers that individual farmers may find difficult to obtain through their own experimentation or social networks —
 precisely the type of nuanced quality assessment that
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "laajaj_macours_forthcoming"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show fails to diffuse through informal channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aggregated peer ratings address key limitations of existing approaches.
 They are based on farmers’ realized production outcomes and therefore reflect seed performance under local conditions.
 They are disseminated directly to farmers,
 allowing the information to reach those who do not typically visit agro-dealers.
 The system is decentralized,
 relying less on institutional capacity.
 Importantly,
 the system does not measure or certify objective seed quality.
 It aggregates farmers' assessments of experienced performance —
 whether the seed they purchased yielded well,
 germinated reliably,
 and tolerated local conditions.
 These assessments may diverge from laboratory measures of seed purity or authenticity.
 Our intervention therefore does not claim to resolve underlying quality problems in the seed supply chain;
 rather,
 it tests whether the gap between non-purchasers' pessimistic beliefs and purchasers' reported experiences reflects a genuine information failure that,
 once addressed,
 leads to welfare-improving adoption decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A striking pattern in our baseline data motivates the central hypothesis.
 On the one hand,
 68% of farmers believe agro-dealer seed is adulterated.
 On the other hand,
 among farmers who actually purchased and used such seed in the recent past,
 ratings are overwhelmingly positive.
 This gap suggests that farmers without direct purchasing experience hold beliefs that are considerably more pessimistic than the experiences of those who have tried the seed.
 We hypothesize that disseminating the experience-based assessments of actual purchasers to the broader farming population can correct this pessimism,
 increase adoption,
 and improve productivity.
 If the belief correction mechanism is the primary channel,
 treatment effects should be concentrated among farmers who had not previously purchased from agro-dealers —
 precisely those whose beliefs are most likely to diverge from the experiences of purchasers.
 This is consistent with
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "laajaj_macours_forthcoming"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who show that farmers can be trapped at local optima,
 holding beliefs about untried inputs that are more pessimistic than warranted,
 and that sufficiently precise exogenous signals can trigger exploration and adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second channel may operate on the supply side.
 By making seed performance assessments visible,
 the rating system creates accountability pressure on agro-dealers,
 who may respond by adjusting their behavior along visible,
 low-cost dimensions.
 If both channels operate,
 they can reinforce each other:
 belief updating increases farmers' willingness to engage with agro-dealers,
 while improved services strengthen the purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial (RCT) involving approximately 3,500 smallholder farmers and 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize seed in eastern Uganda.
 The randomized design allows us to estimate causal effects,
 while three rounds of detailed data enable us to understand how and why the intervention affects behavior.
 We track outcomes along the full causal chain,
 from farmers’ perceptions and adoption decisions to agricultural productivity.
 Additional data on farmers’ choice of agro-dealers,
 agro-dealer practices and services,
 and objective indicators of seed performance allow us to trace the channels through which the intervention operates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the demand side,
 exposure to peer ratings improves farmers’ perceptions of seed performance and increases adoption of high-yielding maize seed,
 with effects concentrated among farmers without prior purchasing experience.
 Treated farmers achieve 13% higher yields,
 reflecting both a shift toward improved varieties and increased investment in complementary inputs.
 On the supply side,
 there is some evidence that agro-dealers respond to accountability pressure by improving service provision and signaling professionalism,
 though these effects are less robust than the demand-side findings.
 We find no evidence that the intervention induces farmers to switch between sellers or improves the underlying performance of seed sold by agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper contributes to the literature on agricultural technology adoption,
 particularly on the role of input quality uncertainty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2023102424"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and farmers’ beliefs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We advance this literature in three ways.
 First,
 we introduce an intervention that addresses limitations of existing seed performance signals —
 it is decentralized,
 experience-based,
 and reaches farmers who do not engage with formal markets —
 and show that it improves adoption and productivity,
 with the strongest evidence for the demand-side belief correction channel.
 Second,
 by tracking outcomes on both sides of the market,
 we examine how demand-side belief updating among farmers and supply-side behavioral responses among agro-dealers may operate as complementary channels,
 providing a more complete picture than studies focusing on buyers or sellers alone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dar2020private"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Third,
 the concentration of effects among farmers without prior purchasing experience provides direct evidence that the gap between these farmers’ beliefs and purchasers’ reported experiences is a binding constraint on adoption in seed markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More broadly,
 this paper connects to a growing literature on crowd-sourced quality information and market outcomes.
 Research on online review platforms documents that consumer feedback affects both sides of the market:
 buyers use reviews to make more informed choices,
 while sellers adjust their behavior in response to public quality signals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/0022051041409075,https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1756-2171.2006.tb00067.x,10.1257/jel.48.4.935,reimers2021digitization"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our study tests whether similar mechanisms operate in a very different setting —
 a low-information,
 offline agricultural input market —
 finding strong evidence for demand-side belief updating and suggestive evidence of supply-side behavioral adjustment in response to aggregated peer ratings.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hasanain2019no"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find a related supply-side effect in Pakistan,
 where crowd-sourced information on livestock insemination services improves veterinarian effort.
\end_layout

