\begin_layout Standard
This section develops a model of how aggregated peer information affects farmers’ adoption decisions and agro-dealer behavior.
 The intervention can operate through two channels:
 by shifting farmers’ beliefs about seed performance (demand side) or by inducing agro-dealers to improve seed performance (supply side).
 The model generates predictions that allow us to distinguish between these channels empirically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Seed purchasing under uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smallholder farmers choose between purchasing seed from agro-dealers and relying on outside options such as farmer-saved seed,
 informal exchanges,
 or seed from public programs.
 The decision depends on beliefs about the performance of agro-dealer seed relative to these alternatives.
 Seed performance has properties of a credence good:
 farmers cannot fully assess it even after use,
 because yields depend on many factors beyond the seed itself.
 This makes individual learning insufficient and beliefs difficult to self-correct,
 creating a role for aggregated peer information that pools many farmers' noisy experiences into an informative signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the performance of seed sold by agro-dealers as experienced by farmers,
 relative to the outside option.
 We decompose experienced performance as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{0}+f(e)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is baseline seed performance and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(e)$
\end_inset

 captures how agro-dealer effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (e.g.,
 investment in handling and storage) affects seed performance.
 The intervention can thus affect farmer outcomes by shifting beliefs about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (demand side) or by shifting 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 itself through 
\begin_inset Formula $f(e)$
\end_inset

 (supply side).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers are risk-averse.
 Farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 adopts seed from an agro-dealer if the certainty equivalent exceeds the cost:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{i}[\theta]-\frac{\rho}{2}\sigma^{2}_{i}-c>0\label{eq:adoption_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is subjective uncertainty about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of absolute risk aversion,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 is the cost of purchasing relative to the outside option.
 Adoption depends on both the level of expected performance and the precision of beliefs:
 even at the same expected return,
 greater uncertainty discourages adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Learning about seed performance from own experience is noisy,
 slow,
 and costly:
 agricultural outcomes depend on many factors beyond seed performance,
 and performance signals arrive only once per season 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "laajaj_macours_forthcoming"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We hypothesize that the resulting belief uncertainty,
 compounded by the disproportionate salience of negative information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "neg_bias,vaish2008not,hornik2015information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 pushes non-purchasers’ beliefs below the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Evidence from fertilizer markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
