 and from maize seed in Uganda 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is consistent with this hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Belief updating through aggregated peer information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When beliefs are imprecise or biased,
 aggregated peer information can shape belief formation.
 The way it does so depends on farmers’ prior purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 holds a prior 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\mid\mathcal{I}_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mu_{i},\sigma^{2}_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 We distinguish two types:

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in P$
\end_inset

) have priors informed by own experience:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

 is moderate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Non-purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in NP$
\end_inset

) lack direct experience:
 we allow 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{NP}<\theta$
\end_inset

 (pessimistic bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NP}>\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

 (greater uncertainty).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention provides a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\theta+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of raters.
 Bayesian updating yields posterior mean and variance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mu}_{i}=(1-\alpha_{i})\mu_{i}+\alpha_{i}s,\quad\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{i}\cdot\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n}{\sigma^{2}_{i}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n},\quad\alpha_{i}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{i}}{\sigma^{2}_{i}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n}\label{eq:updating_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 on the signal is increasing in prior uncertainty.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NP}>\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

,
 non-purchasers place more weight on the signal.
 The belief shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{i}-\mu_{i}=\alpha_{i}(s-\mu_{i})$
\end_inset

 is therefore larger for non-purchasers on both dimensions:
 they weight the signal more heavily (larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

) and the gap between signal and prior is larger (
\begin_inset Formula $s-\mu_{NP}>s-\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 if beliefs are pessimistic).
 For purchasers,
 the main effect is a precision gain (lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

);
 for non-purchasers,
 it is a level shift (higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{i}$
\end_inset

) combined with a precision gain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supply-side responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rating system also creates reputational incentives for agro-dealers.
 When ratings are disseminated to farmers,
 agro-dealers face accountability pressure:
 their customers’ experiences are collected,
 summarized,
 and shared with potential buyers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e\geq0$
\end_inset

 denote dealer effort with convex cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e)$
\end_inset

.
 Effort improves seed performance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{0}+f(e)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f’>0$
\end_inset

.
 Without the intervention (
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

),
 dealers have no reputational incentive beyond the baseline.
 Under the intervention (
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

),
 higher quality translates into higher ratings and increased demand 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R’>0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{e}\quad T\cdot R(\theta_{0}+f(e))+(1-T)\cdot R(\theta_{0})-c(e)\label{eq:dealer_main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

,
 the first-order condition 
\begin_inset Formula $R’\cdot f’(e^{*})=c’(e^{*})$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}>0$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If dealers respond to the intervention by increasing effort,
 seed performance improves and this should be detectable in objective measures.
 If both channels operate,
 they may reinforce each other:
 belief updating increases farmers’ willingness to engage with agro-dealers,
 while improved quality strengthens the purchasing experience.
\end_layout

