\begin_layout Standard
The agro-dealer sample was constructed by listing all agro-dealers across eleven districts in southeastern Uganda,
 drawing on official records of registered agro-dealers and extensive field visits to identify new and informal ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following this census,
 the 348 eligible agro-dealers were assigned to 130 catchment areas (see Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsection: Experimental design"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
 Of the 130 catchment areas,
 65 were assigned to treatment,
 covering 193 agro-dealers,
 and 65 to control,
 covering 155 agro-dealers.
 Across all catchment areas,
 the average number of agro-dealers per area was three,
 with the number ranging from one to 18.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To link agro-dealers with farmers,
 agro-dealers identified the villages where most of their customers reside.
 Enumerators then randomly sampled ten maize-growing households from these villages,
 yielding a sample of approximately 3,500 smallholder farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baseline data were collected from agro-dealers in September-October 2020 and from farmers in April 2021;
 midline data were collected in January-February 2022,
 and endline data in July-August 2022.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the agro-dealer level,
 enumerators interviewed the individual most knowledgeable about day-to-day operations,
 purchased a maize seed bag,
 and recorded indicators related to seed storage conditions.
 At the farmer level,
 enumerators interviewed the individual most knowledgeable about maize farming.
 In addition to general questions,
 farmers listed all maize plots,
 from which one was randomly selected for detailed data collection,
 yielding household-representative averages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Baseline descriptives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subsection describes the baseline sample.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "balance_farmer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports farmer characteristics.
 The average household head is 49 years old,
 78% are male,
 and 51% have completed primary education.
 Households have nine members on average and are located four kilometers from the nearest agro-dealer and nine kilometers from the nearest tarmac road.
 Farmers cultivate three acres,
 have 23 years of maize-growing experience,
 and reported yields of 440 kilograms per acre in the season preceding the baseline survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Half of farmers planted high-yielding maize seed
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

High-yielding maize varieties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to both open-pollinated varieties and hybrids that have been improved through breeding programs.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Farmer-saved seed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to seed of unknown progeny or quality,
 which typically performs worse than freshly purchased high-yielding maize varieties from agro-dealers.
 Our terminology and the rationale for these definitions are detailed in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.1 Context on seeds and their quality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 on at least one plot in that season,
 with one in three purchasing it from an agro-dealer.
 The remainder primarily obtained high-yielding seed from Operation Wealth Creation/National Agricultural Advisory Services or non-governmental organizations,
 while some relied on their own retained seed or farmer-to-farmer exchanges.
 These patterns support Assumption 1,
 indicating that farmers have meaningful outside options to purchasing seed from agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
68% of farmers report believing that maize seed sold by agro-dealers is adulterated.
 This widespread skepticism aligns with Assumption 3,
 which posits that farmers hold prior beliefs about seed performance at agro-dealers that leave room for belief updating to influence adoption decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "balance_dealer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports baseline characteristics of agro-dealers and their shops.
 The average respondent is 32 years old,
 60% are male,
 and over 90% have completed primary education.
 In 55% of cases,
 the respondent is also the owner of the agro-shop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On average,
 agro-shops were established five years before the baseline survey,
 are located seven kilometers from the nearest tarmac road,
 and serve 41 customers per day.
 74% sell only farm inputs and equipment,
 60% provide credit,
 and 46% offer advisory services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the shop manager’s permission,
 enumerators inspected seed storage areas and recorded observable characteristics.
 They reported pest issues (e.g.,
 rats or insects) at 65% of agro-shops and maize seed stored in open containers at 16% of agro-shops.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Enumerators also sampled maize seed bags at the agro-shops and measured their moisture content.
 Moisture is a commonly used objective indicator of seed performance because it directly affects germination and viability;
 additional details are provided in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.1 Context on seeds and their quality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The average moisture content was 13.6%.
 Regarding packaging and labeling,
 68% of purchased seed bags displayed a packaging date,
 18% an expiry date,
 and only 8% a quality certification label issued by the National Seed Certification Services (NSCS),
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In Uganda,
 maize seed certification is overseen by the NSCS within MAAIF.
 Certified seed is identified by a blue tag or sticker,
 while quality-declared seed carries a green tag or sticker.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 consistent with weak baseline guarantees of seed performance provided through agro-shops (Assumption 2).
\end_layout

