\begin_layout Standard
A back-of-envelope calculation suggests that the adoption margin alone cannot fully account for these yield gains.
 Even assuming improved varieties yield 50 percent more than farmer-saved seed,
 the roughly 4 percentage point shift toward agro-dealer sourcing explains only about a quarter of the observed 56 kg/acre increase.
 However,
 the treatment also increases inorganic fertilizer use by approximately 5 percentage points (significant at both midline and endline) and reduces intercropping at midline.
 These complementary input responses are consistent with
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bulte2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who show that uncertainty about seed performance depresses investment in complementary inputs.
 By reducing such uncertainty,
 the ratings intervention encourages farmers to invest more in inputs whose returns depend on seed performance.
 The productivity gains therefore reflect both the direct effect of shifting toward improved varieties and increased complementary input use among farmers who are more confident about the seed they plant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Agro-dealer behavioral responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now turn to the supply-side channel:
 agro-dealer behavioral responses to the rating system.
 By increasing market transparency and creating accountability pressure,
 the intervention incentivizes agro-dealers to adjust their practices.
 Evidence from other contexts shows that public quality disclosure induces sellers to compete over quality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1162/003355303321675428,doi:10.1086/688875,doi:10.1086/734133"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
