\begin_layout Standard
To assess whether agro-dealers adjust their behavior along this margin,
 we examine seed handling and storage practices in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on dealer efforts"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 We construct two indices based on enumerator observations capturing labor-intensive practices (e.g.,
 not storing seed in open containers) and capital-intensive practices (e.g.,
 having a leak-proof roof).
 All variables included in the indices are listed in the table notes.
 Neither of the two indices responds to the intervention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the intervention does not affect seed handling and storage practices,
 agro-dealers appear to respond along other dimensions.
 A third index captures service provision (e.g.,
 recommending complementary inputs) based on agro-dealer-reported variables and is higher among treated agro-dealers,
 with the effect statistically significant at endline.
 A fourth index captures agro-dealer services reported by farmers,
 who likewise observe improved services among treated agro-dealers,
 with the effect statistically significant at midline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agro-dealers also increase participation in activities that signal credibility or professionalism to customers (e.g.,
 membership in a professional association such as UNADA).
 A fifth index capturing signaling practices is higher among treated agro-dealers,
 with the effect statistically significant at endline.
