\begin_layout Standard
This appendix formalizes the conceptual framework in Section 2 as a Bayesian updating model.
 The model makes explicit how aggregated peer ratings affect beliefs and adoption decisions differently for farmers with and without prior purchasing experience,
 and links each prediction to the assumptions stated in the main text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the performance of seed sold by agro-dealers as experienced by farmers,
 relative to the outside option (e.g.,
 farmer-saved seed).
 We decompose experienced performance as
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{0}+f(\mathbf{e})$
\end_inset

,
 where
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is baseline seed performance and
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{e})$
\end_inset

 captures how agro-dealer effort
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 (service provision,
 signaling,
 handling practices) affects the purchasing experience.
 The intervention can thus affect farmer outcomes through two channels:
 by shifting farmers' beliefs about
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (demand side) or by shifting
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 itself through
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{e})$
\end_inset

 (supply side).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers are risk-averse and evaluate the uncertain return to agro-dealer seed against the outside option.
 A farmer adopts if the certainty equivalent of agro-dealer seed exceeds a threshold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{i}[\theta]-\frac{\rho}{2}\sigma^{2}_{i}-c>0\label{eq:adoption}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c>0$
\end_inset

 captures the cost of purchasing relative to the outside option,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's subjective uncertainty about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho>0$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of absolute risk aversion (CARA).
 The mean-variance formulation follows from assuming CARA utility with normally distributed beliefs.
 Under risk aversion,
 adoption depends on both the level of expected performance and the precision of beliefs:
 even at the same expected return,
 greater uncertainty discourages adoption.
 This setup requires that farmers have meaningful outside options [Assumption 1] and that baseline market institutions do not resolve the information problem [Assumption 2].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Prior beliefs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 holds a prior belief about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\mid\mathcal{I}_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mu_{i},\sigma^{2}_{i})\label{eq:prior}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the prior mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the prior variance,
 both conditional on farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's information set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We distinguish two types of farmers based on prior purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in P$
\end_inset

) have direct experience with agro-dealer seed.
 Their priors are informed by own production outcomes,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 is relatively close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

 is moderate [Assumption 4:
 own learning is noisy but informative].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Non-purchasers
\series default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $i\in NP$
\end_inset

) lack direct experience.
 Their priors are formed from locally shared information,
 which may be incomplete or skewed by the disproportionate salience of negative narratives.
 We allow for the possibility that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{NP}<\theta$
\end_inset

 (pessimistic bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NP}>\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

 (greater imprecision) [Assumption 3:
 beliefs are sufficiently imprecise or biased for updating to matter].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The signal from aggregated peer ratings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention provides farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that aggregates the experiences of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 farmers who purchased seed from agro-dealers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\theta+\varepsilon,\quad\varepsilon\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,\frac{\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}}{n}\right)\label{eq:signal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of individual production outcomes around 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Aggregating across 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 farmers reduces the noise in the signal by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 [Assumption 5:
 individual experiences are approximately unbiased,
 so aggregation produces an informative signal].
 The signal is perceived as credible [Assumption 6].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Bayesian updating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon receiving the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

,
 farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 updates beliefs according to Bayes' rule.
 The posterior mean is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mu}_{i}=(1-\alpha_{i})\mu_{i}+\alpha_{i}s,\quad\text{where}\quad\alpha_{i}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{i}}{\sigma^{2}_{i}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n}\label{eq:posterior}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the posterior variance is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}=\frac{\sigma^{2}_{i}\cdot\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n}{\sigma^{2}_{i}+\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}/n}<\sigma^{2}_{i}\label{eq:posterior_var}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 placed on the signal is increasing in prior uncertainty 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and in signal precision 
\begin_inset Formula $n/\sigma^{2}_{\varepsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}_{NP}>\sigma^{2}_{P}$
\end_inset

,
 non-purchasers place more weight on the signal:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{NP}>\alpha_{P}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Differential effects by purchasing experience
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shift in the posterior mean for farmer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\mu}_{i}-\mu_{i}=\alpha_{i}(s-\mu_{i})\label{eq:belief_shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This has two components:
 the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the gap between signal and prior 
\begin_inset Formula $(s-\mu_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Purchasers:

\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{P}$
\end_inset

 is small (prior is relatively precise) and 
\begin_inset Formula $s-\mu_{P}$
\end_inset

 is small (prior is already close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s\approx\theta$
\end_inset

).
 The belief shift is therefore small.
 The main effect is a reduction in posterior variance (precision gain).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Non-purchasers:

\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{NP}$
\end_inset

 is large (prior is imprecise) and,
 if beliefs are pessimistic (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{NP}<\theta$
\end_inset

),
 
\begin_inset Formula $s-\mu_{NP}$
\end_inset

 is large and positive.
 Both components work in the same direction,
 producing a large upward shift in the posterior mean (level shift).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Supply-side channel:
 agro-dealer effort choice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now model the supply-side channel.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{0}+f(\mathbf{e})$
\end_inset

,
 so the intervention can affect experienced seed performance by inducing agro-dealers to change their effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e\geq0$
\end_inset

 denote dealer effort (e.g.,
 investment in handling,
 storage,
 and seed preservation),
 with convex cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e)$
\end_inset

.
 Effort improves seed performance:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\theta_{0}+f(e)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f'>0$
\end_inset

.
 In the absence of the intervention (
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

),
 agro-dealers have no reputational incentive to invest effort beyond the baseline.
 Under the intervention (
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

),
 ratings are collected and disseminated,
 so higher quality translates into higher ratings and increased future demand 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R'>0$
\end_inset

.
 The dealer chooses effort to maximize:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{e}\quad T\cdot R(\theta_{0}+f(e))+(1-T)\cdot R(\theta_{0})-c(e)\label{eq:dealer_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

,
 the first-order condition is 
\begin_inset Formula $R'(\cdot)\cdot f'(e^{*})=c'(e^{*})$
\end_inset

,
 yielding positive effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}>0$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

,
 the marginal return to effort is zero,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If dealers respond to the intervention by increasing effort,
 seed quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 improves,
 and this should be detectable in objective measures of seed performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Predictions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integrated model generates the following testable predictions,
 corresponding to the testable implications in Section 2.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 1 (Perceptions).

\series default
 The treatment shifts perceived seed performance upward.
 The effect is larger for non-purchasers than purchasers,
 because
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{NP}(s-\mu_{NP})>\alpha_{P}(s-\mu_{P})$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from Assumptions 3 (imprecise/biased priors),
 5 (informative signal),
 and 6 (credible signal).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 2 (Adoption).

\series default
 From Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:adoption"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 adoption increases when
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{i}-\frac{\rho}{2}\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 rises above
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 The treatment relaxes this constraint through a higher posterior mean
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{i}$
\end_inset

 (level effect) and a lower posterior variance
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 (precision effect).
 For non-purchasers,
 both channels operate:
 the large upward shift in
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}_{i}$
\end_inset

 combined with reduced uncertainty makes them most likely to cross the adoption threshold.
 For purchasers,
 the level effect is small,
 but the precision effect still operates:
 reduced
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

 lowers the risk penalty
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\rho}{2}\tilde{\sigma}^{2}_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 which can increase adoption at the margin.
 This follows from Assumptions 1 and 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 3 (Productivity).

\series default
 If
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0$
\end_inset

,
 farmers who switch to agro-dealer seed achieve higher yields.
 Reduced uncertainty may also increase investment in complementary inputs,
 amplifying productivity gains.
 This requires Assumption 7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 4 (Agro-dealer switching).

\series default
 The two channels differ in their predictions about switching between agro-dealers.
 Under the demand-side channel,
 peer ratings provide information about the average performance of seed sold by agro-dealers in the farmer's area,
 shifting beliefs about agro-dealer seed in general rather than about any specific dealer.
 This predicts no increase in switching.
 Under the supply-side channel,
 ratings create differential reputational pressure across dealers,
 potentially inducing farmers to reallocate purchases toward higher-rated dealers.
 This predicts increased switching.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Prediction 5 (Seed performance).

\series default
 The two channels generate different predictions about objective seed performance.
 Under the demand-side channel,
 the intervention shifts beliefs but not the product:
 seed quality
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is unchanged.
 Under the supply-side channel,
 if agro-dealers respond to accountability pressure by investing in handling and storage practices,
 objective seed performance can improve.
 Finding no treatment effect on objective seed performance is evidence against a supply-side channel operating through performance improvement,
 and is consistent with the demand-side belief correction channel doing most of the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Context on seeds and their quality
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "A.1 Context on seeds and their quality"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This section has been reviewed and rewritten by David.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study,
 the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-yielding maize varieties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to both open-pollinated varieties (OPVs) and hybrids that have been genetically improved through public or private sector breeding programs.
 While the difference between these two types of maize is based on their reproductive biology,
 there are also economic implications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrisetal1998,SPIELMAN2016111"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We explain the terminology and our rationale for using this terminology below,
 recognizing that our explanation is a simplification of much more complex biological phenomena.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maize hybrids tend to confer a significant advantage in terms of vigor – robust growth,
 high yields,
 and uniform yield performance,
 even under suboptimal conditions.
 This is due to the expression of heterosis that results from crossing distinct inbred parent lines to produce genetically superior progeny (F1) that is planted by the farmer.
 However,
 this vigor declines dramatically if farmers save and plant grain that was set aside from harvest.
 Instead,
 the farmer must purchase fresh (F1) seed each season to continue to realize the benefits of heterosis.
 The combination of vigor and purchase frequency can incentivize public investment in hybrid maize improvement,
 seed production,
 and marketing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
OPVs,
 on the other hand,
 are typically less vigorous than hybrids.
 Although they are also less susceptible to genetic degeneration and can be saved and planted across several generations without loss of vigor,
 their yield performance is typically lower than hybrids.
 Moreover,
 OPV seed saving practices – and thus less frequent purchases of fresh seed – tend to reduce these private investment incentives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relatedly,
 we use the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

farmer-saved seed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this study to refer to seed that is of an unknown progeny or quality.
 They may be seed saved from the harvest of F1 hybrids or OPVs,
 and they may be 
\emph on
n
\emph default
 generations old.
 They may have been stored under suboptimal conditions between seasons,
 exposed to moisture,
 pests,
 or diseases,
 and,
 as a result of both genetic and physical factors,
 perform poorly relative to fresh hybrid or OPV seed purchased from an agro-input shop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As highlighted in a recent review by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MICHELSON2023102424"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 seed quality is complex and multi-dimensional due to the living nature of seeds,
 encompassing three essential dimensions.
 First,
 analytical purity measures the proportion of a seed sample that belongs to the intended species.
 Second,
 varietal purity ensures the seed is of the expected variety,
 possessing the claimed genetic characteristics.
 Third,
 viability and performance assess the seed’s capacity to germinate and grow with sufficient vigor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study focuses on the viability and performance dimension of maize seed quality.
 From a farmer’s perspective,
 this dimension is particularly salient,
 as it represents a crucial outcome that farmers observe during germination,
 early crop growth,
 and harvest,
 although it can be difficult to attribute realized outcomes to seed performance alone.
 Moreover,
 while some storage and handling practices,
 such as seed mixing or mislabeling,
 may affect varietal purity,
 the practices examined in this study primarily influence seed viability and performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Objectively assessing maize seed performance is complex,
 but measuring the moisture content of a seed sample is the most common and practical test.
 Moisture is a powerful predictor,
 as it directly affects germination outcomes.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "afzal2017maintaining"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 e.g.,
 report germination rates of approximately 85% for seeds with a moisture content of 12.7%,
 compared to just 50% for the same seeds at 15.6%.
 Prolonged exposure to high humidity rapidly degrades seed viability by increasing susceptibility to damage from pathogens,
 insects,
 and physical handling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2023102424"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The moisture content of a seed sample reflects recent storage conditions – whether the seeds were kept in airtight packages or exposed to open air.
 Consulted experts emphasized a widely used rule of thumb:
 each one-percentage-point increase in moisture content halves the seed’s shelf life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While moisture measurement is standard practice among seed companies and crop inspectors and provides a valuable indication of seed performance,
 it is inherently one-dimensional.
 Additional quality assessments include germination tests conducted in controlled chambers;
 vigor tests under the growing conditions that may occur in the field;
 grow-out tests,
 which evaluate genetic purity through morphological analysis;
 seed health testing which measures the presence of pathogens and diseases,
 and genotyping (DNA fingerprinting),
 which verifies genetic purity using single nucleotide polymorphism analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rating computation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "A.2 Rating computation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
What if a treated agro-dealer does not receive a single rating?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a treated agro-dealer is not rated by any farmer – e.g.,
 because no sampled farmer had personally purchased seed there or knew someone who had – we informed farmers that we had no information about the shop while still mentioning its existence.
 In the first round,
 16 out of 193 treated agro-dealers were not rated by any farmer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Should more ratings lead to better ratings?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some agro-dealers were not rated by any farmer in the first round,
 while others received up to 22 ratings.
 If agro-dealer A is rated by ten farmers with an average of 3.5 and agro-dealer B is rated by one farmer with a rating of 3.6,
 agro-dealer B is treated as having the higher rating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Should ratings reflect catchment area performance?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ratings were highly concentrated at the upper end of the scale,
 with fewer than 9% of agro-dealers receiving a rating below three out of five.
 Ratings are therefore transformed into quintiles based on their distribution.
 To avoid conveying an overly negative signal,
 the quintile labels were chosen to carry positive connotations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Are female agro-dealers rated worse than male agro-dealers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Significant differences were observed between the ratings of female agro-dealers (41% of the sample) and male agro-dealers (59%),
 even after controlling for potential confounders such as education and multiple performance indicators.
 These differences are unlikely to reflect true disparities in performance and instead appear to stem from biased perceptions,
 likely driven by discrimination 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2024gender"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To mitigate potential harm from the intervention,
 the ratings of female agro-dealers were adjusted accordingly.
 Specifically,
 each seed performance attribute was regressed on a gender dummy,
 and the resulting coefficients were added to the initial ratings of female agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential attrition tests
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "A.3 Differential attrition tests"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To examine differential attrition,
 we regress the pre-registered balance variables (see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "balance_dealer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) on a binary variable indicating whether an agro-dealer left the sample,
 a binary variable indicating whether an agro-dealer belonged to the control group,
 and their interaction.
 Column (2) reveals that agro-dealers who left the sample at midline operated closer to the nearest tarmac road  –  the only significant difference between those who left and those who stayed when attrition was most pronounced (see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Survey-attrition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 By endline,
 however,
 those who left were younger,
 more likely to be female,
 had less established businesses,
 were more likely to operate specialized shops,
 and still tended to be closer to a tarmac road,
 see column (5).
 This suggests that agro-dealers who left differed from those who remained,
 regardless of exposure to the treatment,
 possibly reflecting greater vulnerability during the COVID-19 period,
 leading to business closures.
 Columns (3) and (6) show minimal differences between control and treated agro-dealers,
 consistent with Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "5.3 Orthogonality tests of randomization balance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 Examining the interaction between the indicators reveals few differences between agro-dealers who left the sample 
\shape italic
and
\shape default
 belonged to the control group and those who did not,
 suggesting that differential attrition is unlikely to bias our estimates.
\end_layout

