\begin_layout Subsection
Agro-dealer rating patterns
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Comparison of rating dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We asked farmers to evaluate maize seed sold by an agro-dealer across six dimensions:
 General quality,
 Yield as advertised,
 Drought tolerance as advertised,
 Pest/disease tolerance as advertised,
 Speed of maturing as advertised,
 and Germination.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Comparison of individual ratings"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents the distribution of farmers’ ratings for these attributes along with their mean values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The figure reveals variation across attributes,
 with some showing more concentrated distributions and others exhibiting greater dispersion.
 The attributes most strongly correlated with the 
\shape italic
General quality
\shape default
 rating are 
\shape italic
Yield as advertised
\shape default
 (0.54) and 
\shape italic
Germination
\shape default
 (0.38).
 These two attributes also have the smallest mean absolute differences (0.47 for 
\shape italic
Yield as advertised
\shape default
 and 0.55 for 
\shape italic
Germination
\shape default
),
 suggesting that these are the attributes farmers primarily consider when assessing overall performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Comparison of ratings by purchase channel
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:by purchase channel-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers could rate an agro-dealer if they met one of two conditions:
 either they had purchased seed from the agro-dealer themselves or they knew someone who had.
 Ideally,
 only farmers with firsthand experience would provide ratings,
 but restricting responses in this way risked generating too few observations for a reliable signal.
 While this decision was made at the experiment’s design stage and cannot be revised ex post,
 we can compare endline ratings between farmers who purchased seed from the agro-dealer and those who did not but knew someone who had.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fortunately,
 the vast majority (93%) of ratings came from farmers who had purchased seed,
 while only 7% were provided by those without direct purchase experience.
 This alleviates concerns that ratings are primarily driven by reputation or hearsay effects.
 While the mean ratings differ slightly (3.6 for farmers who bought seed vs.
 3.7 for those who did not),
 the density plots are similar (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Comparison of ratings by purchase channel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Correlating ratings and performance indicators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is concern that smallholder farmers may base their ratings of agro-input shops on factors such as customer service rather than seed performance or rely on the agro-dealer’s reputation or personal relationship with them.
 To address this,
 we test whether the ratings – specifically,
 the index of endline ratings computed following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 – correlate with objective indicators of seller and seed performance,
 also measured at endline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that specialized agro-input shops,
 which exclusively sell farm inputs,
 receive higher ratings,
 as do dealers with better seed handling practices,
 objectively observed by our enumerators (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Ratings & quality indicators - Agro-dealer level"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Also,
 farmers not only rated seeds purchased from agro-input shops but also those used on randomly selected maize fields,
 using the same questions.
 These seed ratings are positively correlated with crop yields (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Ratings & quality indicators on randomly selected field - Farmer level"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While alternative explanations for these significant correlations exist,
 the overall pattern supports our claim that farmers are assessing seed performance.
 The ratings therefore appear to provide an informative signal,
 although farmers’ perceptions may not be perfectly accurate given the many factors influencing agricultural production.
\end_layout

